				<p>Well, kind of. Open loop *assumes* a feedback, where closed loop *measures* a feedback. For example, you may want to move a small vehicle from point A to point B. Not a problem, *as long as you can establish a relationship between motor encoder counts and distance travelled.* This then becomes your feedback - you travel X encoder counts and you *assume* the robot is now at position Y. There is a **model** for how the inputs affect the outputs, and that model becomes the basis for "measuring" (assuming) outputs.</p>
